			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-18854945">

				
				<li class="comment-author">
				
				
				
					<div class="profile" >
						
							






    <img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2011/10/31/muscleguy/950a7e30-3e27-4c9f-b896-e9772708f09b/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />



    <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/id/2467498" title="User profile page">muscleguy</a>



						
						<p class="date">14 October 2012 9:10PM</p>

						<div class="badges">
							
								



							
						</div>
					</div>
				

				

		  
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>I am very, very never bored. But then I am highly educated (PhD), keep myself well informed, read a lot of books, have been to quite a few places, know, have known very interesting people, done a lot of interesting stuff etc so have a lot I can choose to think about if I find myself at a loose end, such as the doctor's waiting room. </p><p>Also in the doing of science you can find yourself engaged in rather tedious and repetitive tasks that nevertheless require great attention and often dexterity and skill. To do these things well you have to develop ways to focus attention for long periods while also thinking of other things, listening to the radio etc. </p><p>I'm also a long distance runner and have run long seriously since I was 14, long before it was practical to carry music players. I never got or get bored even on 3+ hour runs. I might if I had to do them on a treadmill or around a 400m track but I have a variety of courses that change as the seasons do, time of day etc and you train yourself to notice things. In fact the hardest thing can be doing that split brain thing like in science, keeping enough focus on the running to stop the pace from falling while thinking about other stuff or enjoying the day etc. </p><p>So it is partly a matter of practice and enriching your life in enough ways that you have lots of topics you can think about.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
